"1533–Female":"1533–Afdød","1558–Male":"1558–Afdød","1500–Male":"1500–Afdød","1480–Female":"1480–Afdød","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1533":"1533","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","1480":"1480","Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Skotland","Roman Empire":"Roman Empire"},"nl":{"1530–":"1530–Overleden","1530–Male":"1530–Overleden","1533–Female":"1533–Overleden","1558–Male":"1558–Overleden","1500–Male":"1500–Overleden","1480–Female":"1480–Overleden","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1533":"1533","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","1480":"1480","Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Schotland","Roman Empire":"Roman Empire"},"en":{"1530–":"1530–Deceased","1530–Male":"1530–Deceased","1533–Female":"1533–Deceased","1558–Male":"1558–Deceased","1500–Male":"1500–Deceased","1480–Female":"1480–Deceased","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1533":"1533","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","1480":"1480","Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Roman Empire":"Roman Empire","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Baillie","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:","from Older Scots <i>baillie</i>, <i>baili</i>. In Scotland, a baillie was a status name for any of various officials, including the chief magistrate in a barony and (later) the chief magistrate or administrative officer of a barony or district. Etymologically, this is the same word as English   Bailey  , but the functions as well as the spelling of the two officials were different in England and Scotland.","topographic name from Older Scots <i>bailli</i> ‘outer court of a castle’; see   Bailey   3 and   Bale   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Bailie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Baillie  ."]},{"name":"Bailey","meanings":["English: status name for a steward or official, from Middle English <i>bailli</i> ‘manager, administrator’ (Old French <i>baillis</i>, from Late Latin <i>baiulivus</i>, an adjectival derivative of <i>baiulus</i> ‘attendant, carrier, porter’).","English: habitational name from Bailey in Little Mitton, Lancashire, named with Old English <i>beg</i> ‘berry’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","English: occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived by the outer wall of a castle, from Middle English (Old French) <i>bailli</i> ‘outer courtyard of a castle’ (Old French <i>bail(le)</i> ‘enclosure’, a derivative of <i>bailer</i> ‘to enclose’). This term became a placename in its own right, denoting a district beside a fortification or wall, as in the case of the Old Bailey in London, which formed part of the early medieval outer wall of the city."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Baillie was born in 1530, in Roman Empire, his father, 7th of Lamington William Baillie, was 30 and his mother, Jean Hamilton, was 50. He married N.N Home in 1550, in Roman Empire. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1530–":"1530–Surnud","1530–Male":"1530–Surnud","1533–Female":"1533–Surnud","1558–Male":"1558–Surnud","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1533":"1533","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","1480":"1480","Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Roman Empire":"Ro